  "faq": {
    label: "Skater Mode FAQ",
    body: `
    <p>When you put a marshmallow in a vacuum chamber, it crumples and wrinkles and loses its form. Growing up, the first few weeks of summer break were always like that. There was a massive pressure relief, but it was more deflating than relieving. I never really knew what to do with myself. Work wouldn’t start for a week or two, and there was nothing to do. Not nothing to do in the sense that I was bored, but there was nothing compulsory to propel me into action. And so I wouldn’t do much at all.</p>

    <p>There were a few summers, probably between the ages of 14 and 16, where the routine would be to mess around with HTML a little bit, go to the movie theater, walk around aimlessly afterward, and then go home and watch skate clips on YouTube. I think the combination of movies and skate clips got me really attuned to cinematography. With skate clips, most shots are kinetic. The camera follows the skater from a low angle or whips around to catch the run-in before the skater hops on the board and does the trick. They get in the face of security guards and take unique angles to catch jumps and flip tricks. The perspectives are tailored to the form, and most of the conventions come around the advent of the portable camcorder, and so a lot of the aesthetics of the skate clip are vestigial, and they’re given this retro veneer because that’s what skates clips have always looked like. The style, once born of material constraints, becomes a convention to be re-created*. </p>

    <p>One convention that’s emblematic of skate clips is the fisheye lens. You get a wider, panorama style perspective, which allows for more of a trick to be in frame, but it also has an optical distortion that makes the center of the frame much more pronounced than the periphery.</p>

    <p>Anyways, it’s my last summer break for the foreseeable future, and for the first time since high school, I found myself sitting in empty theaters watching limited-release indies, and going home to watch skate clips (lots of Hardies, King, and then the Davonte Jolly/Tyshawn Jones universe). Why not continue the trifecta and start messing around on HTML? So I put together this website (much more sophisticated than anything I was doing back then), and I thought it’d be fun to put it all together with a fisheye lens distortion on the site. Anyways, that’s what skater mode does. It’s a fisheye lens filter for the site. </p>

    <p>I used a canvas for the distortion, so it mimics optical distortion, but the placement for the button is hardcoded in the footer, so when the image distorts, the button doesn’t actually move, so the effect isn’t the easiest to turn off. I might get around to fixing it, but <b>if you want to see how skater mode looks, the button to turn it off should be a little below where it looks like it should be.</b></p>
    <h6>*Kinda like serifs and weighted lines in typography—vestiges of stone carving and manuscript writing respectively, but re-created for print and then again for digital type (essay on this forthcoming).</h6>
    `
  },
